GIT-INJECT(1)                     Git Manual                      GIT-INJECT(1)


NAME
       git-inject - Merge changes into an older commit


SYNOPSIS
       git inject <target> [<patch>]
       git inject [<target>] --staged
       git inject [<target>] --file [FILE...]
       git inject (--continue | --abort | --revert | --clear)


DESCRIPTION
       `git inject` collects the changes in a patch commit on the
       specified branch, then applies the patch diffs to the target
       commit.

       All changes on the current branch that are not in the staging
       area are saved to a temporary area (unless `--working-tree`
       option is supplied to the command) and restored upon successful
       completion of the injection process.

       A target commit is either supplied or assumed. If only `<target>`
       is specified, the changes on the current `HEAD` commit are used
       as the patch.

       If `--working-tree` is supplied and `<target>` is not specified,
       then `HEAD` will be the assumed target commit and the changes
       will be injected into the current `HEAD` commit.

       It is possible that a merge failure will prevent this process
       from being completely automatic.

       You will have to resolve any such merge failure and run
       `git inject --continue`.

       Use `git inject --abort` to stop an injection process, remove the
       `.git/INJECT_STATE/` working files, and return any saved files to
       the working directory.


INSTALLATION
       Copy and paste this command in a terminal. Elevated privileges
       are necessary to install the git-inject documentation.


              curl -fsSL https://dl.clitson.nl/git-inject | sh


       To run the installer locally, clone the repository and then run
       the installation script in an elevated terminal.


              chmod +x install.sh
              ./install.sh --local



MODE OPTIONS
       --continue::
              Resume the injection process after resolving merge
              conflicts. Use this instead of native git continue
              commands.

       --abort::
              Abort the inject operation and reset `HEAD` to the
              original branch and restores any stashed changes.
              Use this instead of native git abort commands.

       --clear::
              Clean up the `git-inject` working state files.


OPTIONS
       <target>
              The older commit that receives the changes. This commit
              must be a direct ancestor of the `<patch>` commit.

       <patch>
              The newer commit containing the changes to merge. If the
              patch commit is on the same branch where the injection was
              started, the commit is removed from the branch history
              during injection.

       --is-empty
              Allow the creation of an empty commit if the patch contains
              no changes or if the changes are already present in the
              target history.

       --into <target>
              Syntactic sugar for positional placement. Inject the patch
              commit into the specified target. Does not alter script
              operation.


SANDBOX
       To create a temporary sandbox to test the command, clone the
       repository then run


              chmod +x ./test/sandbox
              ./test/sandbox setup


       and navigate to the generated 'git-inject-sandbox/' folder and
       open the git project.

       The sandbox is crated with six branches, two of which are orphan
       branches and the other four are split between the orphans, two
       each. The included files are designed to be distinguishable from
       each other by file extension.

       Here's what the tree structure would look like:


              * 82f1807 (feature)           * 6cf071b (reference)
              | * 6c0b3b1 (topic)           | * 41d729a (article)
              | | * b4afe1c (master)        | | * 6316505 (docs)
              | |/                          | |/
              |/|                           |/|
              * | d08a371                   * | 02a7b8f
              |/                            |/
              * 34252d6                     * b6d343a


       The tree is truncated to save space.


GIT
       Not part of the git(1) suite. This is a third-party tool.


